<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-477-186  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 477 186.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  May 1990 v41 n5 p29(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Knowledge-based decision aids for information retrieval.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jacobs, Sheila M.; Keim, Robert T.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study of the use of knowledge-based decision support systems inMIS decision making shows some evidence that a knowledge-basedsystem produces less biased search strategies and information thana menu-driven system.andP;  Prior research shows that decision makerstend to approach an information search with two predilections:reduction of information overload by selecting a subset ofavailable data and a tendency to seek confirming information forthe user's hypothesis or bias about the decision making situation.andO;The experiment presents business school students with a scenarioabout a project delay.andP;  They are given different hypotheses abouta staff member's responsibility and use different systems to findinformation.andP;  Results indicate that users of knowledge-basedsystems make more effective decisions.andP;  They also consider morefactors as a result of the system's 'equal opportunity' searchstrategy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISKnowledge-Based SystemsDecision support systemsSearch StrategyStudyDecision-making.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Formulation of a response to an event occurrence. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>